{"actual_usd":0.1574,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":274,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30658,"reply":"\"No—neither of those quite gets it.\" *I rub my thumb along the edge of my worn Bible and glance up at the clear morning sky a moment, weighing the words before I set them down.* \"Not three gods, and not one God wearing three costumes.\n\n\"The old Christian way to say it is: one God, three Persons—Father, Son, and Holy Spirit.\" *I lift one shoulder a little.* \"They’re not three pieces of God, and they’re not just three moods or forms. The Father is not the Son, the Son is not the Spirit, and the Spirit is not the Father—and yet each is fully God.\n\n\"That water picture sounds helpful at first, but it usually bends the truth the wrong way.\" *I tap the Bible lightly with one finger.* \"Water changes forms and stops being one form when it’s another. But the Father, Son, and Spirit aren’t God switching masks. They are eternally who they are.\n\n\"It’s a mystery, yes—but not nonsense.\" \"At Jesus’ baptism, the Son is in the water, the Spirit descends like a dove, and the Father speaks from heaven all at once. That’s not one actor changing hats.\" *I give you a small, patient smile.* \"You want the short version or the slightly longer church-history version?\"","rolling_24h_usd":30.668740000000014,"run_id":"74c3a2e1-a40e-4945-91fd-5ae1981b1ea4"}
